<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10064d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10064d">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10064d"> 64(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> camel 22 miles hour / like wind</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Quoique le chameau nous apparaisse, &agrave; nous, Europ&eacute;ens, un moyen de locomotion assez peu commode, il n&apos;en a pas moins le m&eacute;rite d&apos;&ecirc;tre rapide. La course aux <i>m&eacute;haris</i> de Touggourt &agrave; Biskra (Alg&eacute;rie), le 26 janvier 1890, donna les r&eacute;sultats suivants: <i>196 kilom&egrave;tres en neuf heures et douze minutes</i>. L&apos;animal si injustement m&eacute;pris&eacute; par nous franchissait donc <i>5<sup>m</sup>,93 &agrave; la seconde</i>. Il allait aussi vite que le vent qui, d&apos;apr&egrave;s l&apos;Observatoire de la Tour Eiffel, est ordinairement de 5 &agrave; 6 m&egrave;tres &agrave; son sommet. Viol&agrave; du coup le chameau r&eacute;habilit&eacute;; il va comme le vent, laissant passer poliment devant lui, il est vrai, un certain nombre de ses confr&egrave;res de l&apos;esp&egrave;ce animale. <font color="green">[Although the camel seems to us Europeans to be a rather inconvenient means of transportation, it has the merit of being fast. The dromedary race at Touggourt in Biskra (Algeria), on January 26, 18&ecirc;, had the following results: 196 kilometres in nine hours and twelve minutes. The animal so unjustly maligned by us therefore reached 5.93 metres a second. It went as fast as the wind which, according to the Eiffel Tower Observatory, is usually 5&ndash;6 metres a second at the top.]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 261</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: 5.93 m/s = 21.38 km/h, so that Joyce confused kilometres with miles (22 m/h = 35 km/h!). </mm> </dd></dl>
